"De Vernal A., Hillaire-Marcel C.","Natural variability of Greenland climate, vegetation, and ice volume during the past million years",2008,"Science","320","5883",,"1622","1625",,,10.1126/science.1153929,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-46249090084&partnerID=40&md5=f99f29d88f425b165bd76aea9edf13a5","GEOTOP Geochemistry and Geodynamics Research Center, Université du Québec À Montréal, succursale Centre-Ville, Montréal, QC H3C 3P8, Canada","De Vernal, A., GEOTOP Geochemistry and Geodynamics Research Center, Université du Québec À Montréal, succursale Centre-Ville, Montréal, QC H3C 3P8, Canada; Hillaire-Marcel, C., GEOTOP Geochemistry and Geodynamics Research Center, Université du Québec À Montréal, succursale Centre-Ville, Montréal, QC H3C 3P8, Canada","The response of the Greenland ice sheet to global warming is a source of concern notably because of its potential contribution to changes in the sea level. We demonstrated the natural vulnerability of the ice sheet by using pollen records from marine sediment off southwest Greenland that indicate important changes of the vegetation in Greenland over the past million years. The vegetation that developed over southern Greenland during the last interglacial period is consistent with model experiments, suggesting a reduced volume of the Greenland ice sheet. Abundant spruce pollen indicates that boreal coniferous forest developed some 400,000 years ago during the ""warm"" interval of marine isotope stage 11, providing a time frame for the development and decline of boreal ecosystems over a nearly ice-free Greenland.",,"boreal forest; climate; coniferous forest; global warming; ice sheet; isotope; Last Interglacial; marine sediment; pollen; sea level change; vegetation; article; climate change; environmental factor; geological time; glacier; Greenland; priority journal; vegetation; bacterial spore; climate; cold climate; ecosystem; growth, development and aging; ice cover; plant; pollen; sediment; spruce; temperature; time; tree; Arctic; Greenland; Picea; Climate; Cold Climate; Ecosystem; Geologic Sediments; Greenland; Ice Cover; Picea; Plants; Pollen; Spores; Temperature; Time; Trees",,,,,,"Dowdeswell, J.A., (2006) Science, 311, p. 963; Rignot, E., Kanagaratnam, P., (2006) Science, 311, p. 986; Luthcke, S.B., (2006) Science, 314, p. 1286; Otto-Bliesner, B.L., (2006) Science, 311, p. 1751; Bennike, O., (2002) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol, 186, p. 1; Willerslev, E., (2007) Science, 317, p. 111; Andersen, K., (2004) Nature, 431, p. 147; Larsen, H.C., (1994) Science, 264, p. 952; Funder, S., (1998) Quat. Sci. Rev, 17, p. 77; Aksu, A.E., Hillare-Marcel, C., Mudie, P., (1989) Proceedings of the Ocean Drilling Program, 105 B, p. 689; Lisiecki, L.E., Raymo, M.E., (2005) Paleoceanography, 20, pp. PA1003. , 10.1029/2004PA001071; Material and methods are available as supporting material on Science OnlineHeusser, L.E., Balsam, W.L., (1977) Quat. Res, 7, p. 45; Sánchez Goñi, M.F., Eynaud, F., Andersen, J.L.K., Shackleton, N.J., (1999) Earth Planet. Sci. Lett, 171, p. 123; Rochon, A., de Vernal, A., (1994) Can. J. Earth Sci, 31, p. 15; Hillaire-Marcel, C., de Vernal, A., (1989) Géographie physique et Quaternaire, 43, p. 263; Bourgeois, J.C., Gajewski, K., Koerner, R.M., (2001) J. Geophys. Res, 106 (D6), p. 5255; Rousseau, D.D., (2006) Rev. Palaeobot. Palynol, 141, p. 277; Hillaire-Marcel, C., de Vernal, A., Bilodeau, G., Weaver, A.J., (2001) Nature, 410, p. 1073; Koerner, R.M., Bourgeois, J., Fisher, D., (1988) Ann. Glaciol, 10, p. 85; Giesecke, T., Bennett, K.D., (2004) J. Biogeogr, 31, p. 1523; Meesters, A.G., Bink, N.J., Henneken, E.A.C., Vugts, H.F., Cannemeijer, F., (1997) Boundary-Layer Meteorol, 85, p. 475; de Vernal, A., Mudie, P.J., (1989) Proceedings of the Ocean Drilling Program, 105 B, p. 401; Overpeck, J.T., (2006) Science, 311, p. 1747; Siegenthaler, U., (2005) Science, 310, p. 1313; Berger, A., Loutre, M.-F., (2002) Science, 297, p. 1287; Kaplan, J.O., 